                            <comment id="15546877" author="vihangk1" created="Tue, 4 Oct 2016 22:33:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;One approach to solve this issue is to mask the values of all the environment variables which have &quot;password&quot; in them. I have tested this approach and it is a one-line change.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The other approach which I can think of is to introduce another config or (reuse &quot;hive.conf.hidden.list&quot; configuration) for environment variables and HiveServer2 will skip providing these environment values.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=spena&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;spena&quot;&gt;spena&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=dlo&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;dlo&quot;&gt;dlo&lt;/a&gt; What do you think? Let me know if you have any better ideas. I am not sure if we should remove all the environment variables from  the output to keep it backwards compatible.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15549667" author="spena" created="Wed, 5 Oct 2016 19:10:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think the best approach would be to avoid printing the environment variables on the client side as it might contain other sensitive values for users that we don&apos;t know. However, we don&apos;t know the impact of removing this, so with your first approach to mask all variables that contain &apos;password&apos; or &apos;pass&apos; works should be good.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15550384" author="vihangk1" created="Thu, 6 Oct 2016 00:16:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=spena&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;spena&quot;&gt;spena&lt;/a&gt; Can you please review the patch?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
